  "headline": "The GFEVD net-transmitter identity is HORIZON-STABLE on the forecasting/operational horizons: it matches the published H=10 baseline at EVERY H>=4 in all 5/5 twins (asia97=Thai, smoke23=WI, flu=TX, flights=LAS, conflict=Niger), and at every H>=2 in 3/5 twins. The ONLY instability is at the very shortest horizon H=1 -- where the generalized FEVD reduces to the contemporaneous innovation covariance Sigma (only the impact matrix A0=I enters, so directed propagation through Phi has not yet acted) and the argmax NET reflects covariance rather than directed transmission: all five twins differ at H=1 (asia97 Singa, smoke23 CT, flu PA, flights PHX, conflict Cameroon). flu and flights take one extra step (still off at H=2: IL, PHX) before locking onto TX / LAS from H=4. DY total connectedness rises monotonically with H in every twin (it never changes the WINNER beyond H>=4). Net: the transmitter is NOT stable at H=1 by construction, but is fully stable and baseline-consistent across all multi-step horizons H in {4,8,12} -- the regime DY connectedness is read at.",
  "note_H1": "At H=1 the Pesaran-Shin GFEVD theta_ij is proportional to Sigma_ij^2/Sigma_jj (pure contemporaneous covariance, no dynamic propagation through Phi), so the H=1 net-transmitter is a covariance artefact, not the directed-contagion transmitter; the directed transmitter emerges and stabilises for H>=2 (H>=4 for flu/flights).",
